神經科學專題討論 (Fall 2010)

課程代號: 3024450 (國防醫學院)、PA116 (陽明大學)
開課老師: 戴晶瑩 博士(分生所)、黃怡萱 博士(生醫所)
時間: 13:30-15:20, 星期一, 9/13/2010-1/3/2011
地點: 中研院生醫所 (Rm #N801/TIGP classroom)
 
The main purpose of this  seminar course is to discuss a couple of landmark papers that lead to develop doctrine  or well acknowledged theory in Neuroscience. The theme of each discussion  follows the course “Introduction of Neuroscience”. The students who enroll the  course are strongly encouraged to participate in the seminar discussion.
 
Aims:
 
1. To bridge the gap between the theory       you hear from the course and the original experiments to derive the theory       in the seminar discussion.
2. To train student’s Q & A       ability and critical thinking.
3. To develop student's discussion skill.
4. To improve student's oral presentation skill (optional, only when we have a       class of >10 students).
 
Class style:
 
This seminar course may  proceed in two different styles depending on the number of students we have.  Nonetheless, all students have to read papers  prior to the class because each one of you will be randomly assigned to explain  one or two figures in the papers. Usually 2 papers (maximum may be 3) will be  assigned for each discussion. The papers are selected by the sit-in professor  and the course organizers, not by students. 
 
If 5-10 students enroll  the class:
 
For each class, one student is responsible for making the Powerpoint  slide. Basically, all you need to do is to copy all the figures from the papers  to a Powerpoint file with reasonable visibility (that means you may have to  break a figure into 2-3 slides if there are many subfigures). We will pick  students randomly to give a background introduction followed by discussion  through figures. The sit-in professor will help us to fill in more background information  in addition to the paper. All you need to do is to read the assigned papers and  let’s together praise or criticize papers through the class with the organizer  (Drs. Chin-Yin Tai or Yi-Shuian Huang) as well as the sit-in professor.
 
If more than 10 students enroll the class:
 
We will team 2 students  in a group for background introduction (5-10 min) and leading discussion. The  two students should work as a team to help each other to prepare background introduction  for the assigned papers. Since it is a formal presentation, you will need to  read a couple of more papers to really understand what authors have described  in their introduction section. You need to prepare slides for background  introduction as well as slides containing figures from papers for other fellow  students to discuss later. Two of you should practice before the class to  ensure each other’s presentation is clear and understandable. Since two of you  work as a team, the presentation score is graded as a group. Be sure to help  each other!  After the introduction, two  of you are responsible to lead the discussion. You can choose whatever ways to  assign other fellow students to go through the figures.
 
Grading:
 
Active participation in the discussion is the key to pass the class. 






