神經科學專題討論 (Spring 2011)

課程名稱:神經科學專題討論(神經科學的現況與挑戰)
課程代號: 3024460 (國防醫學院)、B41EU1900(台灣大學)、25245;PA212(陽明大學)
開課老師: 杜邦憲 博士(生醫所)、陳志成 博士(生醫所)
時間: 13:30-15:20, 星期一, 9/13/2010-1/3/2011
地點: 中研院生醫所 (Rm #N801/TIGP classroom)
 
Current Challenges in  Neuroscience is an interactive seminar course which aims to bring to students up  to date knowledge and to discuss topics that are most provocative, challenging  or paradoxical in neuroscience.

Objectives:

The students will learn to use       multidisciplinary approaches to address issues in Neuroscience. 
The students will understand the       key issues which may further advance Neuroscience.
The students will learn to improve       their interrogative ability and critical thinking.
The students will learn to properly       dissect the information of literature. 
The students will learn to sharpen       their presentation and discussion skills.

 
Class style:
              The course includes  2-3 keynote lectures delivered by invited speakers and ~10 discussion classes which  cover various subjects from basic neuroscience to development of new devices and  to treatment of neurological disorders. The discussion classes are participated  by all registered students, the course masters, and an invited sit-in teacher/expert.  The sit-in professor will assign 1-3 papers (research article, perspective,  opinion, or review) for the class, which all students are required to read prior to the class. At the  class, each student will be randomly assigned to explain one or two figures in  the papers. The sit-in professor will raise critical questions and lead discussion.
 
If 5-10 students enroll  the class:
              For each class, one  student is responsible for making all the figures from the papers into a  Powerpoint file with reasonable visibility. You may have to break a figure into  2-3 slides if there are many subfigures. The course masters will pick some students  to give a background introduction, and others for figures. The sit-in professor  will fill in more background information, and lead the discussion. All students  are to read the assigned papers, and discuss the strength and weakness of the  papers through the class. Students are encouraged to express your own opinions  on the topic discussed.
 
If  more than 10 students enroll the class:
              We will put 2 students on  a group for background introduction (5-10 min), and leading discussion. The two  students should work as a team to help each other to prepare background introduction  for the assigned papers. Since it is a formal presentation, you will need to  read more papers to fully understand what authors described in the introduction  section. You will also prepare slides for background introduction as well as  figures slides from papers for your classmates to discuss later. Two of you should  practice before the class to ensure your presentation is clear and  understandable. Since two of you work as a team, the presentation score is  graded as a group. Be sure to help each other!   After the introduction, two of you are responsible for leading the discussion.  You can decide your ways to guide your fellow students to go through the  figures.  
 
Grading:
              No exam and written  report is required. Active participation in the discussion is the key to pass  the class. 
 
Keynote lectures

Interdisciplinary approaches in       Neuroscience (Brain Mind Welfare Team led by Dr.       Fu-Zen Shaw)
Non-linear phenomena in neural       firing (Dr. Chi-Keung Chan, IOP)
Title to be announced (Dr. Lennart Mucke, Gladstone Institute of Neurological       Disease, USA)

 
Topics for discussion

What are the roles for       extrasynaptic NMDA receptors? (Dr. Chin-Yin Tai, IMB)
How does optogenetics reveal the       brain function? (Dr. Chien-Chang Chen, IBMS)
Can we use our mind to control       neural activity? (Dr. Bai-Chuang Shyu, IBMS)
Can proton be a neural       transmitter? (Dr. Cheng-Chang Lien, NYMU)
Do magnetic receptors exist in       nervous system? (Dr. Ru-Chi Shieh, IBMS)
How does neural       mechanotransduction work? (Dr. Chao-Min Cheng,       Institute of Nanoengineering and Microsystems, NTHU)
Why does block substance P       signal have no analgesic effect on pain in clinical trials? (Dr. Chih-Cheng Chen, IBMS)
How is memory coded? (Dr. Yi-Shuian Huang, IBMS)
Is stem cell therapy future hope       for neurological diseases? (Dr. Hung-Chi Kuo, ICOB)
Can BBB be made more penetrant?       (Dr. Hao-Li Liu, Chang-Gung Memorial Hospital)

 
